				\begin{document}$s_{f_{P}}(t)$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M60"><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>s</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>P</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>(</mml:mo><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mo>)</mml:mo></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq13.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> are identified. The maxima with a prominence lower than 5% of the median of prominences of all maxima are excluded from further analysis, to focus the investigation only on the meaningful low-frequency oscillations. The subsequent analysis is divided into two paths: (A) leads to measuring PAC and building a comodulogram, and (B) results in labeling given coupling as <italic>Reliable</italic> or <italic>Ambiguous</italic> and producing auxiliary plots (Fig. <xref rid="Fig1" ref-type="fig">1</xref>d). The path (A) utilizes sections of the length Δ<italic>t</italic><sub><italic>A</italic></sub> adjusted for each <italic>f</italic><sub><italic>P</italic></sub> to contain 1 cycle, while in the second path (B) to contain 3 cycles of the low frequency to analyze the coupling in a broader context. The maxima occurring earlier than <inline-formula id="IEq14"><alternatives><tex-math id="M61">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\frac {1}{2}\frac {3}{f_{P}}$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M62"><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mfrac class="tfrac"><mml:mrow><mml:mn>3</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>P</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq14.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> or later than <inline-formula id="IEq15"><alternatives><tex-math id="M63">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
