				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\langle f^{max}_{A}-\frac {1}{2}{\Delta } f^{max}_{A},f^{max}_{A}+\frac {1}{2}{\Delta } f^{max}_{A} \rangle $\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M148"><mml:mo>〈</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>−</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mml:mi><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mml:mi><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>〉</mml:mo></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq66.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> corresponds to the maximum of comodulogram taking into account the frequency resolution of the wavelet. This range is the shaded area in the spectrum in Fig. <xref rid="Fig1" ref-type="fig">1</xref>d).</p></list-item><list-item><p id="Par51">A local maximum in frequency for amplitude spectrum should be sought within sets union <inline-formula id="IEq67"><alternatives><tex-math id="M149">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}${f^{M}_{A}} = \langle {f^{m}_{A}}, {f^{n}_{A}} \rangle \cup \langle f^{max}_{A}-\frac {1}{2}{\Delta } f^{max}_{A},f^{max}_{A}+\frac {1}{2}{\Delta } f^{max}_{A} \rangle $\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M150"><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo>〈</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>n</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>〉</mml:mo><mml:mo>∪</mml:mo><mml:mo>〈</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>−</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mml:mi><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mml:mi><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>〉</mml:mo></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq67.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p></list-item><list-item><p id="Par52">It has to be decided which estimate of spectral power to consider for finding a peak, potentially corresponding to the extremum of comodulogram: the average spectrum <inline-formula id="IEq68"><alternatives><tex-math id="M151">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$AS_{f_{P}}(f)$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M152"><mml:mi>A</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>S</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>P</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>(</mml:mo><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mo>)</mml:mo></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq68.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> or spectrum of average <inline-formula id="IEq69"><alternatives><tex-math id="M153">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$SA_{f_{P}}(f)$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M154"><mml:mi>S</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>P</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>(</mml:mo><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mo>)</mml:mo></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq69.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. When the coupled bursts of high-frequency oscillation are strongly synchronized, this high-frequency activity should be more pronounced in the spectrum of average signal than in the average spectrum. Otherwise, the average spectrum is a better choice to look for a peak.</p><p id="Par53">To find out which type of spectrum contains a more pronounced peak, for each spectrum, the sum of power in frequencies (from <inline-formula id="IEq70"><alternatives><tex-math id="M155">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}${f^{M}_{A}}$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M156"><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq70.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> range) where it exceeds the other spectrum is obtained. The spectrum with a higher sum is used for a search of a maximal power value in frequency range <inline-formula id="IEq71"><alternatives><tex-math id="M157">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}${f^{M}_{A}}$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M158"><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq71.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. The frequency corresponding to this maximum is denoted as <inline-formula id="IEq72"><alternatives><tex-math id="M159">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f^{MAX}_{A}$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M160"><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi><mml:mi>A</mml:mi><mml:mi>X</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq72.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> (marked with a blue circle in spectrum in Fig. <xref rid="Fig1" ref-type="fig">1</xref>d). Only proper peaks (with descending slopes on both sides) are considered, hence if the spectrum in <inline-formula id="IEq73"><alternatives><tex-math id="M161">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f^{MAX}_{A}$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M162"><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi><mml:mi>A</mml:mi><mml:mi>X</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq73.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is a top of a rising slope, the coupling is labeled as ambiguous.</p></list-item><list-item><p id="Par54">If <inline-formula id="IEq74"><alternatives><tex-math id="M163">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f^{MAX}_{A} \in \langle f^{max}_{A}-\frac {1}{2}{\Delta } f^{max}_{A},f^{max}_{A}+\frac {1}{2}{\Delta } f^{max}_{A} \rangle $\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M164"><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi><mml:mi>A</mml:mi><mml:mi>X</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>∈</mml:mo><mml:mo>〈</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>−</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mml:mi><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mml:mi><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>〉</mml:mo></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq74.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> the coupling is labeled <italic>Reliable</italic>. Otherwise, the coupling is labeled <italic>Ambiguous</italic>.</p></list-item></list></p>
        <p id="Par55">After repeating all steps described above for each frequency for phase <italic>f</italic><sub><italic>P</italic></sub> and each separate region of significant coupling, the whole comodulogram consists of areas of coupling labeled as <italic>Reliable</italic> or <italic>Ambiguous</italic>. At this point, it is possible to employ one more recommendation presented in Aru et al. (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR1">2015</xref>)—caution in the presence of harmonics. If there is a harmonic structure in the comodulogram and the coupling for a base frequency is labeled as ambiguous, the rest of harmonics is also labeled as ambiguous.</p>
        <p id="Par56">When the labeling process is done, all <italic>Ambiguous</italic> MI values are presented in the comodulogram in shades of gray. The color of shading of frequency ranges in spectrum <inline-formula id="IEq75"><alternatives><tex-math id="M165">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\langle f^{max}_{A}-\frac {1}{2}{\Delta } f^{max}_{A},f^{max}_{A}+\frac {1}{2}{\Delta } f^{max}_{A} \rangle $\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M166"><mml:mo>〈</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>−</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mml:mi><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mml:mi><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>〉</mml:mo></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq75.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> also reflects the coupling label. Finally, each separate <italic>Reliable</italic> and <italic>Ambiguous</italic> region in the comodulogram is outlined with a different color (Fig. <xref rid="Fig1" ref-type="fig">1</xref>e).</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="Sec17">
        <title>Presentation of the results: Comodulogram and Auxiliary plots</title>
        <p id="Par57">The eMI toolbox presents the results of the analysis in three types of plots. The overview is given in the comodulogram (e.g., Fig. <xref rid="Fig1" ref-type="fig">1</xref>e), where the statistically significant coupled pairs of frequencies are marked in color (<italic>Reliable</italic>) or shades of gray (<italic>Ambiguous</italic>). The intensity of the color corresponds to the value of MI evaluated according to Eq. <xref rid="Equ3" ref-type="">3</xref>. Each compact area is outlined with a colored line. The second type of output is the polar phase histogram (e.g., Fig. <xref rid="Fig1" ref-type="fig">1</xref>f). It displays phase histogram for each outlined region from the comodulogram—the color in the phase histogram corresponds to the color of the outline of the area in the comodulogram. Values are normalized by the number of all elements in a given area. A fragment of cosine plotted aside serves as an illustration of how a given phase is related to the time course of low-frequency oscillation. Polar phase histograms are useful when investigating phase relations between various areas on the comodulogram. The third type of output is a composite figure (e.g., Fig. <xref rid="Fig1" ref-type="fig">1</xref>d, panel B). It is especially useful for the interpretation of PAC. It consists of averaged scalograms covering 3 cycles of the low frequency. The black lines outline areas that correspond to the significant coupling in the comodulogram. Below the map, there are two types of signal: average signal <inline-formula id="IEq76"><alternatives><tex-math id="M167">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$S^{B}_{f_{P}}(t)$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M168"><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>S</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>P</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>B</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>(</mml:mo><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mo>)</mml:mo></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq76.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> in turquoise and average low-frequency oscillation <inline-formula id="IEq77"><alternatives><tex-math id="M169">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$SP^{B}_{f_{P}}(t)$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M170"><mml:mi>S</mml:mi><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>P</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>P</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>B</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>(</mml:mo><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mo>)</mml:mo></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq77.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> in black. On the right side, there are two spectra—average spectrum <inline-formula id="IEq78"><alternatives><tex-math id="M171">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$AS_{f_{P}}(f)$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M172"><mml:mi>A</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>S</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>P</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>(</mml:mo><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mo>)</mml:mo></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12021_2020_9487_Article_IEq78.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> in black and spectrum of averaged signal <inline-formula id="IEq79"><alternatives><tex-math id="M173">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
